            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Benjamin Goldberg\u2019s story begins not in San Francisco, but in an orphanage in Seoul, South Korea. Adopted as an infant by a loving Jewish couple\u2014a sociology professor and an architect\u2014he was raised in the intellectual and progressive environment of Berkeley. His name was a gift from his adoptive parents, a bridge between the family he had and the one he would build. Growing up, Ben was fascinated by the intricate systems his parents discussed at the dinner table: social structures from his mother and physical ones from his father. He spent hours watching BART trains slice through the East Bay, captivated by the organized movement of thousands of people.\n\nThis fascination guided him to UC Berkeley, where he pursued a Master's degree in Urban and Regional Planning. He saw transportation not just as a network of roads and rails, but as the circulatory system of a city, vital to its equity and health. Upon graduating, he landed a coveted position as a Transportation Planner for the city of San Francisco.\n\nThe first decade of his career was a study in irony. Ben spent his days designing more efficient transit corridors and bike lanes, only to spend two hours of his own day commuting on an overcrowded bus from a distant neighborhood. This disconnect became a turning point. At 38, he made a conscious decision to fully align his life with his professional philosophy. He sold his small house and moved into a modern, compact condo in Hayes Valley, just blocks from City Hall.\n\nHis 0.0-mile commute is now the cornerstone of his existence. Ben\u2019s mornings start with a walk to a local cafe, followed by a day of work from his home office, analyzing data and drafting policy memos. He is a familiar face at the neighborhood grocery co-op and a member of a small, tight-knit book club that meets monthly. His relationships are deep rather than broad, centered on a few close friends from his university days.\n\nBen\u2019s dream isn\u2019t wealth, but legacy. He hopes to see the completion of a car-free Market Street and the expansion of the Central Subway\u2014projects he has poured years into. He sees San Francisco as a beautiful, flawed organism that he has a profound responsibility to nurture. For Ben Goldberg, his neighborhood isn't just a place to live; it's the living, breathing proof of his life's work."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nAt eight, he pressed his face against the cool glass of a BART train emerging from the Transbay Tube. San Francisco unfolded below\u2014a living circuit board, a flash of understanding. It wasn't just a view; it was a revelation that the city wasn\u2019t buildings, but connections. His mother discussed social systems and his father physical ones, but here, he saw them fused together in silent, speeding motion. That moment planted a seed of purpose: he wouldn\u2019t just watch the city\u2019s circulatory system; he would help it flow.\n\n2.\nHe was ten, sitting on the living room floor, when his parents explained his name. His mother said \u201cBenjamin\u201d was for hope, and his father said \u201cGoldberg\u201d was for welcome. They told him his story wasn\u2019t one of being left, but of being found. He felt no confusion, only a profound sense of placement. He wasn\u2019t just their son; he was a bridge between worlds, living proof that a family, like a city, could be intentionally and beautifully built. That security became his unshakable foundation.\n\n3.\nAt 37, stranded on a packed 38 Geary in a downpour, he saw his own exhausted reflection in the fogged window. He\u2019d spent the day drafting a policy to reduce bus travel times, and here he was, a prisoner of the very problem he was paid to solve. The irony wasn't academic anymore; it was a suffocating, damp weight. In that moment of crowded misery, a decision crystallized with absolute clarity. He wouldn't just plan a better city in theory; he would embody it in practice.\n\n4.\nHis first morning in the Hayes Valley condo, age 38. The city sounds were different here\u2014closer, softer. Instead of a frantic rush, he walked three minutes to a local cafe. Holding the warm cup, he looked toward City Hall, his \u201coffice,\u201d and felt a sense of profound rightness settle over him. It wasn't a grand victory, but a quiet, internal click of alignment. For the first time, his life and his life\u2019s work occupied the same small, perfect map. This feeling became his new definition of success.\n\n5.\nStanding on a deserted platform late one night in his early forties, he watched the first test train for the Central Subway glide silently into the station. He wasn't an official observer, just a planner who needed to see it. The clean hum, the sheer reality of it\u2014a project he\u2019d poured years of data and advocacy into\u2014made his chest tighten with pride. This was the city\u2019s new artery, and he had helped map its course. It was a tangible piece of his legacy, humming with quiet promise."
        },
